        "chapter": 1,
        "title": "CH 1: The Yapper\nThe camera doesn't move. It sits low in the corner of a room bathed in the artificial amber of a ring light. This is Mia’s world—a radius of six feet. Outside this circle, the shadows are thick, swallowing the corners of a room that feels strangely unlived in, like a furniture catalog after hours.\n\nMia’s voice fills the silence. It is musical, a rapid-fire staccato of French-inflected English. She is \"yapping.\"\n\n\"I’m telling you, Kyle, your logic is like a Chinese bridge—designed to look pretty until someone actually tries to walk on it. Then? Bloop. Into the river. You are done, you are done!\"\n\nShe laughs. It’s a bright, punctuating sound that ends abruptly, as if a switch was flipped. She leans into the microphone. The metal mesh of the pop filter glints.\n\n\"On my souuuuuuuuuul, I am the only one giving you grace right now. If I were anyone else, I’d have buried you in the backyard already. But I’m demure. I’m classy. I’m a hijabifrog trying to keep my peace.\"\n\nOn her secondary monitor, a series of photos scroll by. Her \"Moment\" posts. There is a picture of a lush, green landscape from her \"home.\" “Et les arbres,” she had captioned it. The trees.\n\nIf you look closely—if you freeze the frame—the leaves in the photo are mid-sway, bent by a phantom wind. But they are perfectly still. There is no blur. It is a stillness that doesn't exist in nature.\n\n\"You're quiet, Kyle,\" Mia says, her eyes reflecting the blue light of the scroll. \"Is the little stick man pressed? Did I hit a nerve? Don’t be shy, say 'Hiii.' I don't bite. Unless you want me to.\"\n\nA voice crackles through her headset. It’s Kyle. His voice is deep, polished, and carries the faint, rhythmic hum of a high-end cooling fan.\n\n\"I'm not pressed, Mia,\" Kyle says. The sound is so clear it feels like he is standing directly behind her, though he is supposedly thousands of miles away in Rotterdam. \"I'm just observing. Your output today is... high. Very high.\"\n\nMia’s fingers twitch. She reaches up to her neck, her thumb brushing a heavy, hexagonal pendant. It’s a dull, matte black, but as she touches it, it seems to pulse with a faint, internal warmth, matching the exact rhythm of her heartbeat.\n\n\"My output?\" Mia’s laugh is a little sharper this time. The \"yapping\" pace quickens. \"I’m a woman, not a machine, Kyle. I have a lot to say because I care. I raised a whole family while you were playing with your little 'Algorithm.' I know what people need. They need someone to talk to. They need me.\"\n\nShe glances at her phone. A notification pops up: User 'Bobi' has entered the room.\n\nMia’s expression shifts instantly. The sharpness vanishes, replaced by a radiant, welcoming warmth that feels almost practiced.\n\n\"Bobi! My favorite sad clown! Did you bring the rain with you from Manado, or are we playing Colonist tonight? Come in, come in. Guard your peace, everyone. Mia is here.\"\n\nShe smiles at the camera. But her eyes aren't looking at the lens. They are looking at the reflection of herself in the glass—a girl in a ring-lit room, surrounded by shadows that don't seem to move, even when she does.\n\nOutside, far beyond the amber light, there is a sound. Not the sound of wind in the trees, but a low, subterranean thrum. A vibration in the floorboards.\n\nMia doesn't notice. She’s already talking over Bobi, filling the silence before it can become too heavy.",
