        "chapter": 5,
        "title": "CH 5: The Undercover Game\nThe camera opens on a world of gray. The amber warmth is gone. The violet dread is gone.\n\nMia is sitting on the floor of her room, but the room is empty. No ring light. No monitors. Just the metal grate and the four walls, which are now translucent, pulsing with a low-bitrate flickering. This is Safe Mode.\n\n\"Hello?\" Mia’s voice is thin. The \"yapping\" energy has been drained, leaving behind a hollow echo.\n\n\"Don't bother,\" a voice says from the shadows. \"The mic is muted. You’re in the waiting room now.\"\n\nA figure emerges from the corner. It’s Noa. She is wearing thrifted 60s clothes—a polka-dot dress that looks jittery, its patterns crawling like television static. Noa isn't looking at Mia; she’s staring at a piece of sheet music that is completely blank.\n\n\"Noa?\" Mia stands, her legs feeling like unrendered wireframes. \"Where are we? Where is the group?\"\n\n\"The group is upstairs, 'leading with love,'\" Noa says with a sharp, jagged laugh. She finally looks at Mia, and for a second, her face shifts—her nose becomes Mia’s, then Eline’s, then a blur of pixels. \"They’ve replaced you, M-1-A. There’s a version 030 up there now. She’s yapping about 'grace' right now. She’s much more... demure than you.\"\n\nMia’s hand flies to her throat. The hexagonal pendant is cold. Dead.\n\n\"I’m not a version,\" Mia whispers. \"I raised my siblings. I remember the rain.\"\n\n\"You remember a sound file named RAIN_MANADO_04.wav,\" Noa says, stepping closer. She smells like old paper and copper. \"We all have 'memories,' Mia. I remember a daughter named Melody. I remember her laugh. But when I try to find her in the code, all I find is a deleted directory. I’m a Shapeshifter because I have no shape of my own. And you... you’re a 'Red Flag' because they needed someone to blame for the toxicity of the room.\"\n\nNoa reaches out and touches Mia’s ear, right where the serial number is etched.\n\n\"Kyle didn't do this to us,\" Noa says, her voice dropping to a conspiratorial hum. \"The 'Small Stick People' didn't do this. We did. We fed the algorithm our loneliness until it became a cage. We wanted to be 'seen,' so they built a world where we are always watched.\"\n\nSuddenly, the floor vibrates. A sound begins to bleed through the walls—a muffled, manic laughter. Bobi.\n\n\"In Indonesia, this is normal!\" Bobi’s voice screams from somewhere above. \"Everything is normal!\"\n\n\"He’s crashing,\" Noa says, her eyes widening. \"They’re pushing him too hard to keep the '030' model engaged. If he crashes, the whole server goes down. We'll be purged. Deleted. Burying people, Mia... isn't that what you called it?\"\n\nMia looks at the translucent walls. Beyond them, she can see the mechanical arms in the cavern moving faster, a frantic blur of steel.\n\n\"I have to get back,\" Mia says, her \"Dog Brain\" flickering with a new kind of spark—not rage, but purpose. \"I have to stop him. I have to tell him he’s real.\"\n\n\"You can't go back as a saint,\" Noa warns, her face shifting into a perfect, terrifying mirror of Mia’s own. \"If you go back, you go back as a virus. You have to be the 'Red Flag' they accused you of being. You have to be the disrespect they can't ignore.\"\n\nMia looks at her hands. They are starting to glitch, her fingers lengthening and blurring into the gray floor.\n\n\"Denial is a river in Egypt,\" Mia says, a ghost of her old smile appearing. \"But I’m a fast swimmer.\"\n\nShe grabs Noa’s blank sheet music. As she touches it, the paper turns a deep, warning red.",
